MajorDuties:
This position requires extensive coordination and coalition building with executive program sponsors and stakeholders internal and external to the DoD, such as the Joint Staff, Combatant Commands, Military Department and agency Program Executive Officers, DoD Chief Information Office (CIO), Under Secretary of Defense (USD) for Acquisition and Sustainment (A&S), General Services Agency, Department of Homeland Security, and other federal agencies. Establishes broad management concepts for information technology requirements for current and proposed capacity and operates a program management structure to control information technology activities. Major responsibilities include: a. Under the guidance of the USD (A&S) and Component Acquisition organization for acquisition matters and the Director for Digital Capabilities & Security (DCS) Center, providing planning and critical recommendations for the acquisition planning, development, operation and maintenance of Information Technology, Systems, and Enterprise Services, in conjunction with and close coordination with internal and external stakeholders. b. Delivering information systems to the Director, Enterprise Operations & Infrastructure (EOI), and enabling the customers, warfighters to meet functional, strategic, and operational goals. Services include assisting the functional organization with the definition of the technical requirements for information systems that include but are not limited to:
(1) Providing information processing, storage, transport, and display capabilities, information technology operation, and maintenance of the utility;
(2) Introducing innovative business practices in the delivery of information technology;
(3) Directing the performance of day-to-day technical support through use of analytical and business presentation techniques; and
(4) Execute DOD CIO approved plans to sustain current legacy systems and to migrate from these legacy systems to the future enterprise capabilities as documented in the DISA Campaign Plan and Analysis of Alternatives. c. Soliciting acquisition requirements from stakeholders and customers DoD-wide and in some cases Fed-wide; extensive outreach communications with the private sector to identify technology to most cost effectively meet the DoD requirements and mission objectives.

